Issues.Title: Required types and 'This method/object is not implemented by design.'
Issues.Body:
While trying to put our codebase on core3 rails, we faced unexpected exception that frustrated us.
 
The following types are strongly necessary for our application:
- System.Drawing.Design.ToolboxItem
- System.ComponentModel.Design.ComponentDesigner 
 
But we catch this exception: 
System.NotImplementedException: 'This method/object is not implemented by design.' 
 
Could you confirm that these types are in your plan and will be implemented in release v3.0?
 
We are also waiting for the following types from the System.Design lib:
- System.ComponentModel.Design.UndoEngine
- System.ComponentModel.Design.DesignSurface 
- System.ComponentModel.Design.InheritanceService 
- System.ComponentModel.Design.DesignerActionMethodItem
- System.ComponentModel.Design.DesignerActionPropertyItem
 
Can we expect to see all the missed types in the final release?
Issues.RelatedDescription: Open issue "Required types and 'This method/object is not implemented by design.'" (#469)

Issues.Title: ComboBox’s text cannot be partially selected when using mouse slides
Issues.Body:
**OS:** RS5 X64
**VS:** Dev16 16.0.0 Preview 4.0 [28612.88.d16.0]
**.NET SDK:** .NET Core 3.0.100-preview-010334 from release branch

**More info:**
The issue reproduce on when setting the "DropDownStyle" property value of the Combobox control is "Sample"/"DropDown".

**Steps to Reproduce:**
1.  Open the attached .NET Core application and run it.([\\mlangfs1\public\Winforms\v-zhgl\ComboboxIssue\CoreApplication.zip](url))
2. Try to select partially text in the Combobox control using mouse slides.

**Actual**: ComboBox’s text cannot be partially selected when using mouse slides
![comboboxissue](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38325459/53146214-549b8180-35de-11e9-813e-012b3a6ad75e.gif)

**Expexted**: ComboBox’s text can be partially selected when using mouse slides

Issues.Title: Refactor Clipboard to make it testable
Issues.Body:
Related to #416

Ideally we would refactor clipboard code so that all calls to win32 OLE* methods are exposed by a single class (OleClipboard) and published as a public interface and a constructor that takes object that implements that interface as a parameter. Then the test will mock the IOleClipboard interface and use constructor that takes this mock as a parameter.
Issues.RelatedDescription: Open issue "Refactor Clipboard to make it testable" (#459)

Issues.Title: Support IDragSourceHelper/IDragTargetHelper?
Issues.Body: These two interfaces are used to support enhanced drag-and-drop support, including (most importantly for me) the ability to specify a custom image to be displayed under the cursor during the drag. While this can be done in C# today by using COM interop, you have to roll your own `IDataObject` implementation to do so, as the default Windows Forms one does not support setting arbitrary COM-based private formats into the data object, per Windows requirements. Would it be possible to update the Windows Forms `DataObject` class to enable this? (It would be even better if there would be higher-level code added to obviate the need to do custom COM interop to use thesee features, but I do not know what the API design for that would look like.) Thanks!
Issues.RelatedDescription: Open issue "Support IDragSourceHelper/IDragTargetHelper?" (#457)

Issues.Title: SuppressMessage Which one to keep, which one to remove?
Issues.Body:
A search of our repo indicates that we use the SuppressMessage attribute on the following Microsoft.* binaries:

* Performance
* Reliability
* Design
* Usage
* Portability
* Interopability
* Reliability
* Security
* Globalization
* Naming

It would be useful in the future (mostly because we are occasionally porting components from framework) to create a list about the SuppressMessages that we would like to keep or get rid of. If it's possible to come up with such a list.

In PR #439 I am adding Microsoft.Usage.
Issues.RelatedDescription: Open issue "SuppressMessage Which one to keep, which one to remove?" (#448)
